name: Camel
description: Camels are desert-dwelling animals that can survive long periods without water. Their humps store fat, not water, which can be converted to energy. They have adapted to extreme heat and sandstorms with thick eyelashes and closable nostrils.

name: Cheetah
description: Cheetahs are the fastest land mammals, reaching speeds up to 70 mph in short bursts. Their lightweight bodies, large nasal passages, and long tails help them balance and sprint efficiently. Unlike other big cats, they cannot roar, but they chirp and purr.

name: Chimpanzee
description: Chimpanzees are our closest living relatives and share many behaviors with humans. They use tools, form alliances, and express a range of emotions. Socially complex, chimps live in large communities and are skilled problem-solvers.

name: Crocodile
description: Crocodiles are ancient reptiles with powerful jaws and strong tails. They ambush prey near water edges and can remain submerged for long periods. With armored skin and strong bite force, they are among the most formidable aquatic predators.

name: Elephant
description: Elephants are the largest land animals on Earth, known for their intelligence, strong family bonds, and complex emotions. Their trunks serve as tools for feeding, drinking, and communicating. They also use low-frequency sounds to communicate over long distances.

name: Flamingo
description: Flamingos are wading birds known for their bright pink feathers, which come from eating shrimp and algae rich in carotenoids. They feed by filtering water with their curved beaks and often stand on one leg to conserve body heat.

name: Giraffe
description: They are the world’s tallest mammals. They are uniquely adapted to reach vegetation inaccessible to other herbivores. Unusually elastic blood vessels and uniquely adapted valves help offset the sudden buildup of blood (to prevent fainting) when giraffes’ heads are raised, lowered, or swung quickly. Their "horns" are actually knobs covered with skin and hair above the eyes that protect the head from injury. Their necks contain the same amount of vertebrae as we do (seven) except their bones are extremely elongated making their neck a long length of 2.4 meters.

name: Gorilla
description: Gorillas are the largest primates and share about 98% of their DNA with humans. They live in family groups led by a silverback male and communicate with gestures, vocalizations, and facial expressions. They are gentle, intelligent, and endangered.

name: Hippopotamus
description: Despite their bulky appearance, hippos are aggressive and fast, especially in water. They spend much of their time submerged to keep cool and communicate with grunts. Their powerful jaws and territorial behavior make them dangerous.

name: Hyena
description: Hyenas are known for their bone-crushing jaws and scavenging habits, but they are also skilled hunters. Living in matriarchal clans, hyenas use vocalizations and social intelligence. They play an important role in cleaning up ecosystems.

name: Kangaroo
description: Kangaroos are marsupials native to Australia, recognized by their strong hind legs, long tails, and pouches where joeys develop. They move by hopping at high speeds and can cover great distances. Social animals, they live in groups called mobs or troops.

name: Koala
description: Koalas are marsupials found in eucalyptus forests of Australia. They feed almost exclusively on eucalyptus leaves, which are toxic to most animals. Koalas sleep up to 20 hours a day due to their low-energy diet and have specialized stomachs to digest toxins.

name: Leopard
description: Leopards are stealthy, solitary big cats that are excellent climbers and swimmers. They often drag their prey into trees to keep it safe from scavengers. Their rosette-spotted coats provide excellent camouflage in dense forests and grasslands.

name: Lion
description: Lions are powerful predators and the only big cats to live in groups called prides. Males are known for their iconic manes, while lionesses handle most of the hunting. They use coordinated tactics, strength, and teamwork to bring down prey in open savannas.

name: Meerkat
description: Meerkats are small, social mammals that live in groups called mobs. They take turns standing guard while others forage. Meerkats have excellent vision, strong digging claws, and a cooperative lifestyle that helps protect against predators.

name: Orangutan
description: Orangutans are highly intelligent apes with reddish-brown hair. They live in trees and use tools to access food. Orangutans have long arms and strong hands adapted for climbing and swinging. They are critically endangered due to habitat destruction.

name: Ostrich
description: Ostriches are the worldâ€™s largest birds and cannot fly, but they can run at speeds of up to 60 km/h (37 mph). They use their powerful legs for defense and have keen eyesight. Native to Africa, they lay the largest eggs of any living land animal.

name: Panda
description: Giant pandas are native to China and are known for their distinctive black and white coats. Despite belonging to the order Carnivora, they eat mostly bamboo. They have strong jaw muscles to crush stalks and are solitary, spending up to 14 hours a day feeding.

name: Peacock
description: Peacocks are male peafowls known for their iridescent tail feathers, which they fan out in displays to attract mates. Their tail eyespots and vibrant colors are used in courtship. They are ground-dwellers and roost in trees for safety at night.

name: Penguin
description: Penguins are flightless birds adapted to life in the water. They use their flipper-like wings to swim at high speeds, and their dense feathers provide insulation in cold climates. Most species live in the Southern Hemisphere, with some in Antarctica.

name: Rhinoceros
description: Rhinos are large, thick-skinned herbivores known for their prominent horns. They have poor eyesight but a strong sense of smell and hearing. Despite their size, rhinos can run up to 30 mph. They are endangered due to poaching and habitat loss.

name: Sloth
description: Sloths are tree-dwelling mammals that move extremely slowly to conserve energy. They sleep up to 20 hours a day and rely on algae and moss growing in their fur for camouflage. Their strong grip and curved claws help them hang motionless from branches.

name: Snow Leopard
description: Snow leopards are elusive big cats adapted to cold mountainous regions. Their thick fur and long tail provide warmth, and their large nasal cavities help breathe in thin air. These solitary hunters are threatened by habitat loss and poaching.

name: Tiger
description: Tigers are solitary and territorial big cats with striped coats that provide excellent camouflage in forests. They are apex predators and rely on stealth to stalk prey. Each tiger's stripe pattern is unique, like a fingerprint. They are strong swimmers too.

name: Wolf
description: Wolves are highly intelligent and social animals that live in structured packs. They use howling for communication and have complex hunting strategies. Wolves help control prey populations and play a crucial role in maintaining healthy ecosystems.

name: Zebra
description: Zebras are social herbivores known for their black-and-white stripes, which are unique to each individual and may help confuse predators or regulate body temperature. They live in herds and migrate long distances in search of food and water across African plains.
